Exploring the Relationship Between Financial Statement Items and Stock Performance

Patrick Johnson and Anh Pham

Exploring How Financial Statement Items Relate to Stock Performance

1. Motivation: Why This Topic Matters

When people talk about why a stock goes up or down, they often focus on one number: earnings per share (EPS).
However, companies publish hundreds of financial numbers every year in their official filings with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC).

This project asks a simple but important question:

Besides earnings, do other financial numberssuch as assets, liabilities, or depreciationhelp explain how a companys stock price changes over time?

Understanding this is valuable because stock prices are influenced by how strong or risky a company appears to investors. This tutorial aims to make the topic approachable for beginners, even if you have no background in accounting or finance.

This project aims to solve what financial professionals, phds, and professional hedge fund managers aim to solve. Is there some formula or model that can predict stock prices??? We want to explore just some of the complexities of this task from a data science perspective

Project Goals

The goal of this project is to analyze and determine how different financial statement indexes correlate with stock price changes for companies in the S&P 500 over the past ten years. Instead of focusing on the most common measure, earnings per share (EPS), we want to see if factors like depreciation, assets, or liabilities also help explain stock performance. By finding these correlations, we hope to better understand how financial decisions and company internal set up are reflected in investor behavior and market value.

Furthermore, we want to predict market cap (total market value of all of the shares) which would get us to price per share, using most recent shares outstanding, a feature defined in the edgar documentation. This is a more robust way to make models that predict stock prices because market cap is scaled to the metrics in the dataset, unlike stock prices which don't mean much without knowing how many shares outstanding exist. Price per share share is stock split adjusted in the Yfinance documentation.

Project Dataset

The datasets we are considering working with are the SEC EDGAR Financial Statement Metrics and Yahoo Finance Historical Stock Data. Together, these two datasets will allow us to examine how companies internal financial structures influence their external market performance over time. Our goal is to identify relationships between balance sheet and income statement items, especially those unrelated to earnings per share (EPS) (such as depreciation and total liabilities), and stock price trends for firms in the S&P 500 index.

The SEC EDGAR dataset provides standardized financial statement information of publicly traded U.S. companies, including variables like total assets, total liabilities, depreciation, and operating income. The Yahoo Finance dataset contains corresponding market data such as daily closing prices and trading volumes. By organizing the stock data by year and linking it to the financial data from EDGAR using company tickers or IDs, we can create one dataset that shows both a companys financial performance and its market value

This integration will allow us to answer questions such as: How do changes in liabilities or depreciation expenses relate to changes in stock prices? Do firms with more asset growth correlate to higher long-term stock performance? Combining these two datasets bridges the gap between corporate accounting and investor behavior, providing a comprehensive foundation for analyzing how internal financial indicators translate into market outcomes.

Glossary

  • CIK (Central Index Key): A unique 10-digit identifier assigned by the SEC to every entity that files with EDGAR, including public companies, mutual funds, and individuals. Used to look up filings in SEC APIs and EDGAR.

  • start: The beginning date of the reporting period for the reported XBRL fact. Used for facts that cover a period (e.g., revenue for a quarter or year). Example: "start": "2024-01-01"

  • end: The ending date of the reporting period for the fact. This, combined with start, defines the timeframe for period-based financial metrics.Example: "end": "2024-09-30"

  • val: The numeric value of the XBRL-reported fact (e.g., revenue, assets, operating income). Usually appears as a raw number without formatting. Example: "val": 73582000000 (which is 73.582B)

  • accn (Accession Number): A unique EDGAR-generated ID for the specific filing containing this fact. You can use it to locate the filings directory and document list. Example: "accn": "0001652044-24-000118"

  • fy (Fiscal Year): The fiscal year associated with the filing (not necessarily the calendar year). Companies with non-December year-ends may have FY differing from calendar year. Example: "fy": 2024

  • fp (Fiscal Period): The fiscal period represented by the filing. Common values include: Q1 = First fiscal quarter

  • filed: The date the filing was submitted to the SEC EDGAR system.

  • frame: A special time-period code used by XBRL for instant or duration frames.

Before we begin working with the data, we will explain the financial terms and how these elements are used in later codes. Our project focuses on analyzing companies in the S&P 500, a list of the 500 leading stock exchange companies in the U.S.

What is a Ticker? A ticker, also called a stock symbol, is a short and unique abbreviation used to identify a publicly traded company in the stock market. A company is assigned a ticker when it goes public and trades stocks the first time. For example: Apples ticker is AAPL, Googles is GOOGL, and Walmart is WMT. Tickers exist to prevent name confusion as many companies share similar names/terms.

Pull in all tickers to feed into CIK - Ticker conversion

Later in this project, we will collect official financial information for each company from the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). The SEC assigns each company a special ID number called a CIK (Central Index Key). However: The SEC does NOT recognize stock tickers (only CIK numbers). To access financial filings, we must convert the companys ticker into a CIK number. Then use the CIK to request the financial data.

In this step, we will download a table from stockanalysis.com that lists all companies in the S&P 500.

We then read that table into Python and pull out the column that contains the company ticker symbols (for example: AAPL, MSFT, GOOG). These tickers will be used later to help us match each company to its CIK code in the SEC database.

Step 2: Map Tickers to SEC CIK Numbers

The SEC identifies companies by CIK (Central Index Key) numbers, not ticker symbols. This cell downloads the official SEC ticker-to-CIK mapping and matches each S&P 500 ticker to its corresponding 10-digit CIK number, which is required to access SEC EDGAR filings.

In[3]:
import requests
import pandas as pd

# The SEC requires us to include a user-agent when making requests
headers = {
    'User-Agent': 'Your Company Name pjohnson3@tulane.edu',
    'Accept-Encoding': 'gzip, deflate'
}

# Download the SEC file that lists tickers and their CIK numbers
CIK = requests.get('https://www.sec.gov/include/ticker.txt', headers=headers)

# Turn the text file into a dictionary: {Symbol : CIK}
ticker_map = dict(line.split('\t') for line in CIK.text.upper().strip().split('\n') if line)

# Convert the dictionary into a DataFrame for easier use
ticker_map = pd.DataFrame(list(ticker_map.items()), columns=['Symbol', 'CIK'])

# Make sure all CIKs are 10 digits long (add leading zeros if needed)
ticker_map['CIK'] = ticker_map['CIK'].astype(str).str.zfill(10)

# Remove duplicate CIK numbers to keep the table clean
ticker_map = ticker_map.drop_duplicates(subset='CIK', keep='first')

# Match S&P 500 tickers with their CIK numbers
sp500_cik = pd.merge(sp500_tickers, ticker_map, on='Symbol', how='left')

# Print preview to ensure everthing works
print(sp500_cik.head())
print(f"Total symbols: {sp500_cik['Symbol'].count()}")
print(f"Unique CIKs: {sp500_cik['CIK'].nunique()}")
print(f"\nSample CIKs (should be 10 digits):")
print(sp500_cik[['Symbol', 'CIK']].head(10))

Step 4: Extract Financial Data from SEC EDGAR

This is the core ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) step. For each company, we:

  1. Query the SEC EDGAR API for all reported financial facts (us-gaap and dei namespaces)
  2. Extract shares outstanding data separately for market cap calculations
  3. Parse XBRL-formatted financial statements into a structured DataFrame
  4. Track the most recent shares outstanding for each company

Note: Companies without shares outstanding data are dropped since we need this for market cap calculations.

In[5]:
import pandas as pd
import requests

# Assuming CIK_list and sp500_cik are already defined
namespaces = ['us-gaap', 'dei']
all_edgar_df = pd.DataFrame()  # To store US-GAAP metrics
all_shares_df = pd.DataFrame() # To store Shares Outstanding
SHARES_FACT_NAME = 'EntityCommonStockSharesOutstanding'

for cik in CIK_list:
    edgar_api = f'https://data.sec.gov/api/xbrl/companyfacts/CIK{str(cik).zfill(10)}.json'
    try:
        edgar_response = requests.get(edgar_api, headers={'User-Agent': 'Example App YourName@example.com'})
        edgar_response.raise_for_status()
        data = edgar_response.json()
    except requests.exceptions.RequestException as e:
        print(f"Error fetching CIK {cik}: {e}")
        continue

    financial_data = []
    shares_data = []

    try:
        ticker = sp500_cik.loc[sp500_cik['CIK'] == str(cik).zfill(10), 'Symbol'].iloc[0]
    except IndexError:
        print(f"Warning: Ticker not found for CIK {cik}. Skipping.")
        continue

    for namespace in namespaces:
        if namespace in data.get('facts', {}):
            for fact_name, fact_details in data['facts'][namespace].items():
                if 'units' in fact_details:
                    for unit_type, records in fact_details['units'].items():
                        for record in records:
                            record_dict = {
                                'fact_name': fact_name,
                                'label': fact_details.get('label', ''),
                                'description': fact_details.get('description', ''),
                                'unit': unit_type,
                                'value': record.get('val'),
                                'start_date': record.get('start'),
                                'end_date': record.get('end'),
                                'filed_date': record.get('filed'),
                                'form': record.get('form'),
                                'frame': record.get('frame', ''),
                                'fiscal_year': record.get('fy'),
                                'fiscal_period': record.get('fp'),
                                'accn': record.get('accn'),
                                'company_cik': data.get('cik'),
                                'company_name': data.get('entityName'),
                                'Ticker': ticker
                            }
                            if fact_name == SHARES_FACT_NAME:
                                shares_data.append(record_dict)
                            else:
                                financial_data.append(record_dict)

    # Conditional Logic to Drop Company (from previous fix)
    if not shares_data:
        print(f"*** WARNING: Dropping company {ticker} (CIK {cik}) because no '{SHARES_FACT_NAME}' data was found. ***")
        continue

    all_edgar_df = pd.concat([all_edgar_df, pd.DataFrame(financial_data)], ignore_index=True)
    all_shares_df = pd.concat([all_shares_df, pd.DataFrame(shares_data)], ignore_index=True)
    print(f"Loaded {len(financial_data)} metric records and {len(shares_data)} shares records for {ticker}")

# --- CLEAN SHARES DATA AND GET CURRENT SHARES ---

# Rename value column for clarity
all_shares_df.rename(columns={'value': 'Shares_Outstanding'}, inplace=True)

# Convert dates
all_shares_df['end_date'] = pd.to_datetime(all_shares_df['end_date'], errors='coerce')
all_shares_df['filed_date'] = pd.to_datetime(all_shares_df['filed_date'], errors='coerce')

# Drop duplicates: keep the last record per Ticker + filed_date
all_shares_df = all_shares_df.sort_values(['Ticker', 'filed_date', 'end_date'])
all_shares_df = all_shares_df.drop_duplicates(subset=['Ticker', 'filed_date'], keep='last').reset_index(drop=True)

print("\n--- Cleaned Shares Outstanding Sample ---")
print(all_shares_df[['Ticker', 'end_date', 'filed_date', 'Shares_Outstanding']].head())

# GET CURRENT SHARES OUTSTANDING FOR EACH TICKER
current_shares_dict = {}
for ticker in all_shares_df['Ticker'].unique():
    ticker_shares = all_shares_df[all_shares_df['Ticker'] == ticker].sort_values('end_date', ascending=False)
    if len(ticker_shares) > 0:
        current_shares_dict[ticker] = ticker_shares.iloc[0]['Shares_Outstanding']

print("\n--- Current Shares Outstanding by Ticker ---")
for ticker, shares in current_shares_dict.items():
    print(f"{ticker}: {shares/1e9:.2f}B shares")

# ADD CURRENT SHARES TO ALL_EDGAR_DF
all_edgar_df['Current_Shares_Outstanding'] = all_edgar_df['Ticker'].map(current_shares_dict)

print(f"\n Added Current_Shares_Outstanding column to all_edgar_df")
print(f"Sample:")
print(all_edgar_df[['Ticker', 'fact_name', 'value', 'Current_Shares_Outstanding']].head())

Cleaning the EDGAR Data

The raw EDGAR dataset contains many fields that we do not need for this project. Since our goal is to study how financial statement items relate to stock price changes, we only keep the columns that provide:

  • fact_name: the name of the financial metric
  • value: the reported value
  • start_date, end_date, filed_date: the reporting dates
  • form: the form type (10-K, 10-Q, etc.)
  • fiscal_year, fiscal_period: the fiscal year/period
  • Ticker: the company ticker

We remove metadata columns such as descriptions, internal SEC IDs, and text fields that do not contribute to numerical analysis. This makes the dataset cleaner and easier to use for correlation and price-change calculations.

Step 8: Prepare Shares Outstanding Data We clean and deduplicate the shares outstanding data to create a lookup table. For each company at each reporting date, we will have the number of shares outstanding, which is essential for converting between stock price and market capitalization.

Step 9: Define Quarterly Normalization Function

SEC filings report financial metrics in different time periods:

  • Quarterly (Q1-Q4): Direct quarterly values
  • Year-to-Date (YTD): Cumulative values (e.g., Q3 YTD = Q1+Q2+Q3)
  • Full Year (FY): Annual totals

This function normalizes all data to quarterly values by:

  1. Identifying the reporting period type based on date ranges
  2. Calculating individual quarter values from YTD figures (e.g., Q2 = Q2_YTD - Q1)
  3. Extracting Q4 from FY values (Q4 = FY - Q3_YTD)

This ensures all metrics are comparable across the same time granularity.

In[9]:
def q_normalize(variable):
    variable = variable.copy()

    # Check if start_date column exists
    if 'start_date' not in variable.columns:
        return variable

    # FIX: Convert dates to datetime at the very beginning
    variable['start_date'] = pd.to_datetime(variable['start_date'], errors='coerce')
    variable['end_date'] = pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date'], errors='coerce')

    # Remove rows with invalid dates
    variable = variable.dropna(subset=['start_date', 'end_date'])

    # Remove comparative data by keeping only the earliest filing for each end_date + fiscal_period
    if 'filed' in variable.columns:
        variable['filed'] = pd.to_datetime(variable['filed'], errors='coerce')
        variable = variable.sort_values('filed')
        variable = variable.drop_duplicates(subset=['end_date', 'fiscal_period'], keep='first')

    variable_narrowed = pd.DataFrame(columns=variable.columns)

    for _, row in variable.iterrows():
        start = row['start_date']  # Already datetime
        end = row['end_date']      # Already datetime

        # Compute days difference
        days_diff = (end - start).days

        if days_diff < 100:
            # Keep actual quarterly data (days < 100)
            variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, row.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)
        else:
            # Handle FY -> Q4 conversion (FY - Q3 YTD)
            if row['fiscal_period'] == 'FY':
                q4 = row.copy()
                q4['fiscal_period'] = 'Q4'
                q4['start_date'] = end - pd.DateOffset(months=3)

                # Get Q3 YTD matching rows - same end_date year
                q3_ytd_match = variable.loc[
                    (variable['end_date'].dt.year == end.year) &
                    (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q3') &
                    ((variable['end_date'] - variable['start_date']).dt.days > 100)
                ]

                # Subtract Q3 YTD value if it exists
                if not q3_ytd_match.empty:
                    q4['value'] = float(q4['value']) - float(q3_ytd_match.iloc[0]['value'])
                    variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q4.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)

            # Handle Q2 YTD -> extract Q1 and Q2
            elif row['fiscal_period'] == 'Q2':
                # METHOD 1: Try to find actual Q2 (days < 100) - same end_date year
                q2_actual_match = variable.loc[
                    (variable['end_date'].dt.year == end.year) &
                    (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q2') &
                    ((variable['end_date'] - variable['start_date']).dt.days < 100)
                ]

                if not q2_actual_match.empty:
                    # We have actual Q2, so calculate Q1 = Q2_YTD - Q2_actual
                    q1 = row.copy()
                    q1['fiscal_period'] = 'Q1'
                    q1['end_date'] = start
                    q1['start_date'] = start - pd.DateOffset(months=3)
                    q1['value'] = float(row['value']) - float(q2_actual_match.iloc[0]['value'])
                    variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q1.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)
                else:
                    # METHOD 2: No actual Q2 found, try Q1 YTD method
                    q1_ytd_match = variable.loc[
                        (variable['end_date'].dt.year == end.year) &
                        (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q1') &
                        ((variable['end_date'] - variable['start_date']).dt.days > 100)
                    ]

                    if not q1_ytd_match.empty:
                        # Calculate Q2 = Q2_YTD - Q1_YTD
                        q2 = row.copy()
                        q1_ytd_end = q1_ytd_match.iloc[0]['end_date']
                        q2['start_date'] = q1_ytd_end
                        q2['value'] = float(row['value']) - float(q1_ytd_match.iloc[0]['value'])
                        variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q2.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)

                        # Also extract Q1 from Q1_YTD if it doesn't exist as actual
                        q1_actual_match = variable.loc[
                            (variable['end_date'].dt.year == end.year) &
                            (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q1') &
                            ((variable['end_date'] - variable['start_date']).dt.days < 100)
                        ]

                        if q1_actual_match.empty:
                            q1 = q1_ytd_match.iloc[0].copy()
                            variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q1.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)

            # Handle Q3 YTD -> extract Q3
            elif row['fiscal_period'] == 'Q3':
                # METHOD 1: Try to find actual Q3 (days < 100) - same end_date year
                q3_actual_match = variable.loc[
                    (variable['end_date'].dt.year == end.year) &
                    (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q3') &
                    ((variable['end_date'] - variable['start_date']).dt.days < 100)
                ]

                if q3_actual_match.empty:
                    # METHOD 2: Calculate Q3 = Q3_YTD - Q2_YTD - same end_date year
                    q2_ytd_match = variable.loc[
                        (variable['end_date'].dt.year == end.year) &
                        (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q2') &
                        ((variable['end_date'] - variable['start_date']).dt.days > 100)
                    ]

                    if not q2_ytd_match.empty:
                        q3 = row.copy()
                        q2_ytd_end = q2_ytd_match.iloc[0]['end_date']
                        q3['start_date'] = q2_ytd_end
                        q3['value'] = float(row['value']) - float(q2_ytd_match.iloc[0]['value'])
                        variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q3.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)

    # Sort by end_date FIRST before deduplication
    variable_narrowed = variable_narrowed.sort_values('end_date')

    # Deduplicate by keeping one row per end_date
    variable_narrowed = variable_narrowed.drop_duplicates(subset=['end_date'], keep='first')

    return variable_narrowed

Step 10: Apply Quarterly Normalization

We apply the normalization function to every financial metric for every company. This loops through each ticker and each unique financial fact, converting all values to quarterly periods.

Step 11: Group Features into Quarterly Windows

Financial filings often contain multiple facts reported on the same date. We:

  1. Create quarterly period identifiers (e.g., 2023Q1)
  2. Group all financial metrics that belong to the same quarter
  3. Identify the latest filing date per quarter to ensure we are using the most current data
In[11]:
# Ensure dates are datetime type
normalized['end_date'] = pd.to_datetime(normalized['end_date'], errors='coerce')
normalized['filed_date'] = pd.to_datetime(normalized['filed_date'], errors='coerce')
normalized = normalized.dropna(subset=['end_date', 'filed_date'])

# Create quarterly periods to group filings within 90 days
normalized['quarter'] = normalized['end_date'].dt.to_period('Q')

print(f"Unique (Ticker, Quarter) pairs: {normalized.groupby(['Ticker', 'quarter']).ngroups}")

# For each quarter, find the LATEST filed_date (most recent filing)
latest_filing_per_quarter = normalized.groupby(['Ticker', 'quarter'])['filed_date'].max().reset_index()
latest_filing_per_quarter.columns = ['Ticker', 'quarter', 'best_filed_date']

print(f"Latest filing dates identified for {len(latest_filing_per_quarter)} quarters")

# Merge back to associate each row with the best filing date for that quarter
normalized = normalized.merge(
    latest_filing_per_quarter,
    on=['Ticker', 'quarter'],
    how='left'
)

DAYS_AFTER = 5

# Prepare price data
yahoo_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(yahoo_df['Date'], errors='coerce', utc=True)
yahoo_df = yahoo_df.dropna(subset=['Date'])

# Get unique quarters
unique_quarters = normalized[['Ticker', 'quarter', 'best_filed_date']].drop_duplicates()

print(f"Processing {len(unique_quarters)} unique quarters...")

results = []

for idx, row in unique_quarters.iterrows():
    ticker = row['Ticker']
    filing_date = row['best_filed_date']

    ticker_prices = yahoo_df[
        (yahoo_df['Ticker'] == ticker) &
        (yahoo_df['Date'] > filing_date)
    ].copy()

    if len(ticker_prices) >= DAYS_AFTER:
        avg_price = ticker_prices.iloc[0:DAYS_AFTER]['Close'].mean()

        results.append({
            'Ticker': ticker,
            'quarter': row['quarter'],
            'best_filed_date': filing_date,
            f'Avg_Price_{DAYS_AFTER}_Days': avg_price
        })

quarter_price_data = pd.DataFrame(results)

print(f"\nCalculated prices for {len(quarter_price_data)} quarters")
print(f"Average price: ${quarter_price_data[f'Avg_Price_{DAYS_AFTER}_Days'].mean():.2f}")

PIVOT TO WIDE FORMAT (ONE ROW PER QUARTER). Now we convert the financial data from a "long" format (where each financial fact is a separate row) into a "wide" format (where each financial fact becomes a separate column), making the data ready for operations like finding correlations and our model. Step 14: Pivot Data to Wide Format

Transform from long format (one row per metric) to wide format (one row per company-quarter with metrics as columns). This creates a feature matrix where:

  • Each row = one company at one quarter
  • Each column = one financial metric (e.g., Revenue, Assets, Liabilities)

This is the format required for machine learning models.

Step 15: Analyze Feature Sparsity

A critical data quality check. We analyze what percentage of values are missing for each financial metric. SEC EDGAR data is notoriously sparse because:

  • Different companies report different metrics
  • Companies use different XBRL tags for similar concepts
  • Reporting requirements vary by industry

Key Finding: Most features have >90% missing values, which significantly limits model performance.

Step 16: Clean Features and Define Target

We prepare features for modeling by:

  1. Replacing infinite values with NaN
  2. Capping extreme outliers at the 1st and 99th percentiles (winsorization)
  3. Defining our feature matrix (X) and target variable (y = Market Cap)
  4. Applying log transformation to Market Cap to handle exponential growth patterns
In[16]:
import numpy as np
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")


for col in feature_columns:
    # Replace infinities with NaN
    metrics_wide[col] = metrics_wide[col].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)

    # Cap extreme outliers at 1st and 99th percentile
    q99 = metrics_wide[col].quantile(0.99)
    q01 = metrics_wide[col].quantile(0.01)
    metrics_wide[col] = metrics_wide[col].clip(q01, q99)

Step 17: Remove Perfectly Correlated Features

Features with correlation > 0.99 to the target are likely spurious - they typically appear in only 1-2 samples and create the illusion of perfect predictive power. Removing these prevents overfitting to noise.

    try:

Step 20: Time-Based Train/Test Split

We split data chronologically (80% train, 20% test) rather than randomly. This is crucial for time-series data because:

  • We cannot use future information to predict the past
  • This simulates real-world conditions where we train on historical data and predict forward
  • It prevents data leakage that would inflate performance metrics
In[20]:
# 80/20 time-based split

Step 21: Model 1 - Aggregate XGBoost

Our baseline model trains a single XGBoost regressor on all companies combined. This assumes the relationship between financial metrics and market cap is the same across all companies and sectors.

Approach: Predict log(Market Cap) then convert to price using shares outstanding

In[21]:
from xgboost import XGBRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

RANDOM_STATE = 42

model_aggregate = XGBRegressor(
    n_estimators=200,
    max_depth=6,
    learning_rate=0.1,
    subsample=0.8,
    colsample_bytree=0.8,
    random_state=RANDOM_STATE,
    n_jobs=-1
)

print("Training aggregate model...")
model_aggregate.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict in log scale
y_pred_aggregate_test_log = model_aggregate.predict(X_test)

# Transform back from log to actual market cap
y_pred_aggregate_test = np.expm1(y_pred_aggregate_test_log)

# Convert to prices
pred_prices_aggregate_test = y_pred_aggregate_test / shares_test.values

agg_test_r2 = r2_score(actual_prices_test, pred_prices_aggregate_test)
agg_test_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual_prices_test, pred_prices_aggregate_test))

print(f" Model 1 Results:")
print(f"  Test R: {agg_test_r2:.4f}")
print(f"  Test RMSE: ${agg_test_rmse:.2f}")

Step 23: Model 3 - Individual Ticker Models

Instead of one model for all companies, we train a separate model for each company with sufficient data (20 or more samples). This allows each company to have its own unique relationship between financials and valuation.

Fallback: Companies without enough training data use the aggregate model.

In[23]:
ticker_models = {}
unique_tickers_train = reference_train['Ticker'].unique()

MIN_ROWS_PER_TICKER = 20

print(f"Training individual models for tickers with {MIN_ROWS_PER_TICKER} samples...")

for ticker in unique_tickers_train:
    ticker_mask_train = reference_train['Ticker'] == ticker
    ticker_X_train = X_train[ticker_mask_train]
    ticker_y_train = y_train[ticker_mask_train]

    if len(ticker_X_train) < MIN_ROWS_PER_TICKER:
        continue

    ticker_model = XGBRegressor(
        n_estimators=100,
        max_depth=4,
        learning_rate=0.1,
        random_state=RANDOM_STATE,
        n_jobs=-1
    )

    ticker_model.fit(ticker_X_train, ticker_y_train)
    ticker_models[ticker] = ticker_model
    print(f"   {ticker}: trained on {len(ticker_X_train)} samples")

print(f"\nTrained {len(ticker_models)} individual ticker models")

# Make predictions
pred_market_cap_individual_test = np.zeros(len(X_test))

for i in range(len(X_test)):
    ticker = reference_test.iloc[i]['Ticker']

    if ticker in ticker_models:
        # Predict in log scale
        pred_log = ticker_models[ticker].predict(X_test.iloc[i:i+1])[0]
    else:
        # Fall back to aggregate model
        pred_log = model_aggregate.predict(X_test.iloc[i:i+1])[0]

    # Transform from log to actual market cap
    pred_market_cap_individual_test[i] = np.expm1(pred_log)

# Convert to prices
pred_prices_individual_test = pred_market_cap_individual_test / shares_test.values

individual_test_r2 = r2_score(actual_prices_test, pred_prices_individual_test)
individual_test_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual_prices_test, pred_prices_individual_test))

print(f" Model 3 Results:")
print(f"  Test R: {individual_test_r2:.4f}")
print(f"  Test RMSE: ${individual_test_rmse:.2f}")

# DEBUG
print(f"\nDEBUG Model 3:")

Step 24: Model 4 - Ensemble

We combine predictions from all three models using weighted averaging:

  • 30% Aggregate model
  • 30% Sector model
  • 40% Individual ticker models

Ensemble methods often outperform individual models by balancing their strengths and weaknesses.

In[24]:
w1, w2, w3 = 0.3, 0.3, 0.4

pred_prices_ensemble_test = (
    w1 * pred_prices_aggregate_test +
    w2 * pred_prices_sector_test +
    w3 * pred_prices_individual_test
)

ensemble_test_r2 = r2_score(actual_prices_test, pred_prices_ensemble_test)
ensemble_test_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual_prices_test, pred_prices_ensemble_test))

print(f" Model 4 Results:")
print(f"  Test R: {ensemble_test_r2:.4f}")
print(f"  Test RMSE: ${ensemble_test_rmse:.2f}")

  • R squared: How much variance the model explains (1.0 = perfect, negative = worse than mean baseline)

Key Finding: All models show negative R squared, indicating the financial metrics alone are insufficient to predict stock prices accurately.

# Get unique tickers in test set
unique_test_tickers = reference_test['Ticker'].unique()
n_tickers = len(unique_test_tickers)

print(f"Creating plots for {n_tickers} tickers (4 per page)...")

# Calculate predictions for ensemble  FIXED (no .values)
ensemble_pred_mc = np.asarray(pred_prices_ensemble_test) * np.asarray(shares_test)

# Group tickers into pages of 4
tickers_per_page = 4
n_pages = (n_tickers + tickers_per_page - 1) // tickers_per_page

for page in range(n_pages):
    start_idx = page * tickers_per_page
    end_idx = min(start_idx + tickers_per_page, n_tickers)
    page_tickers = unique_test_tickers[start_idx:end_idx]

    n_plots = len(page_tickers)

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_plots, 1, figsize=(16, 5*n_plots))
    if n_plots == 1:
        axes = [axes]

    fig.suptitle(
        f'Market Cap Predictions (Ensemble Model) - Page {page+1}/{n_pages}',
        fontsize=16, fontweight='bold'
    )

    for idx, ticker in enumerate(page_tickers):
        # Get data for this ticker
        ticker_mask = (reference_test['Ticker'] == ticker).values
        ticker_indices = np.where(ticker_mask)[0]

        ticker_dates = reference_test.iloc[ticker_indices]['best_filed_date'].values
        ticker_actual_mc = np.expm1(y_test.iloc[ticker_indices].values) / 1e9
        ticker_pred_mc = ensemble_pred_mc[ticker_indices] / 1e9

        # Sort by date
        sort_idx = np.argsort(ticker_dates)

        # Plot market cap
        ax = axes[idx]
        ax.plot(
            ticker_dates[sort_idx], ticker_actual_mc[sort_idx],
            'o-', label='Actual Market Cap',
            color='blue', alpha=0.7, markersize=6, linewidth=2
        )
        ax.plot(
            ticker_dates[sort_idx], ticker_pred_mc[sort_idx],
            'o-', label='Predicted Market Cap',
            color='orange', alpha=0.7, markersize=6, linewidth=2
        )

        # Error fill
        ax.fill_between(
            ticker_dates[sort_idx],
            ticker_actual_mc[sort_idx],
            ticker_pred_mc[sort_idx],
            alpha=0.2, color='gray', label='Prediction Error'
        )

        # Metrics
        ticker_r2 = r2_score(ticker_actual_mc, ticker_pred_mc)
        ticker_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(ticker_actual_mc, ticker_pred_mc))
        ticker_mape = np.mean(
            np.abs((ticker_actual_mc - ticker_pred_mc) / ticker_actual_mc)
        ) * 100

        ax.set_ylabel('Market Cap ($B)', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')
        ax.set_title(
            f'{ticker} - R = {ticker_r2:.4f}, RMSE = ${ticker_rmse:.2f}B, '

Conclusion

In conclusion, predicting stock price through financial metrics alone is a very complicated process both from the ETL side and the modeling side as well. The data from EDGAR is too sparse and too inconsistant to meaningfully produce results, and the best models, we observe, come from the models that are company-specific.The comparison across the four modeling approachesAggregate, Aggregate + Sector, Individual Tickers, and the Ensembleclearly demonstrates that granularity and customization are key. Models that attempt to find a "one-size-fits-all" relationship across all companies and sectors (Models 1 and 2) struggle to capture the unique financial DNA of each firm.

We CAN, however, find metrics that are positively correlated to stock prices. We know, for example, revenue is highly correlated because of the nature of the earnings effect of that variable (income/expense).

But because there are so many variables, utilizing simple models like linear regression dilutes the true correlative power of the features because they cannot account for the complex, non-linear interactions inherent in financial markets. This necessitates the use of more sophisticated, non-linear ensemble methods like XGBoost, which can better handle the high-dimensional, noisy nature of this data.

There probably IS some model or formula out there that predicts stock prices, we look at Jim Simons fund for example which uses quantitative finance to outperform the market consistantly over decades. To accomplish that, however, requires intense dedication to the ETL required and a profound understanding of the variables and trends that exist not only in the SEC documentation but in the macroeconomic and qualitative sources as well.
